+# Tech Stack Research: sokoban
+
+> Research output — recommended technology stack for a web-based 10-level Sokoban game
+> (HTML5 Canvas 2D, TypeScript, pure frontend, GitHub Pages deploy). Alternatives compared
+> per open direction; locked constraints (TS, Canvas 2D, Vite, npm, Vitest+Playwright,
+> GitHub Pages, Conventional Commits, no backend) are **not** re-debated here.
+
+---
+
+## Recommendation
+
+**Vanilla TypeScript + Vite-native `import.meta.glob` + `requestAnimationFrame` tween +
+Pointer Events + raw localStorage**, tested with Vitest (happy-dom) and Playwright — the
+simplest viable stack for 10 levels, a single developer, and zero scale concerns. No state
+library, no animation library, no swipe library, no storage wrapper. Each "no" is justified
+below against 2+ alternatives; complexity is added only where it earns its keep (and the
+only earned addition is `happy-dom` for fast unit tests).
+
+Confidence labels: **HIGH** = verified against current npm registry / Vite docs / known
+behavior; **MEDIUM** = well-established pattern but not directly verified in this session;
+**LOW** = speculative, depends on future ecosystem behavior.
+
+---
+
+## Comparison by Direction
+
+### Direction 1 — Level Loading Strategy
+
+How the 10 `levels/level-XX.json` files reach the running game. Locked: each level is a
+separate JSON file under `levels/` (not hardcoded in TS).
+
+| Criterion | A: `import.meta.glob('./levels/*.json', { eager: true, query: '?json' })` (Vite built-in) | B: `fetch('./levels/level-XX.json')` at runtime | C: Build-time copy (`vite-plugin-static-copy`) + dynamic `import()` per level | Recommendation |
+|-----------|---------|---------|---------|---------|
+| Works on GitHub Pages static host | **Yes** — JSON inlined into JS bundle, no network round-trip, no path/base issues (HIGH) | **Fragile** — relative paths break under repo-subdir `base`; needs `import.meta.env.BASE_URL` prefixing everywhere (HIGH) | **Yes** — files copied to `dist/`, but still needs correct `base` for fetch/dynamic import (MEDIUM) | A |
+| Bundle size impact | 10 small grids (~1–3 KB each) → ~10–30 KB added to bundle; negligible (HIGH) | Zero added to bundle; fetched at runtime | Same as A but split across dynamic chunks | A (size irrelevant at this scale) |
+| Type safety on level data | Returns `Record<string, ParsedJson>`; cast once through a `parseLevel()` Zod-free validator (HIGH) | Returns `unknown` from `res.json()`; same manual validation needed | Same as A | Tie (A slightly nicer: import map is static) |
+| Dev ergonomics / HMR | Eager glob is resolved at build/dev start; editing a JSON file hot-reloads (HIGH) | Need to refetch on change; no HMR | Dynamic import cache-busting needed | A |
+| Extra dependencies | None — Vite native | None — native `fetch` | `vite-plugin-static-copy` (~2 deps) | A |
+| Failure mode | Compile-time error if `levels/` is empty → caught before deploy | 404 at runtime → blank level in production | Missing file → runtime dynamic-import rejection | A |
+
+**Recommendation: A — `import.meta.glob`.** For 10 tiny levels on a static host with a
+repo-subdir base path, inlining via eager glob removes an entire class of path/base/fetch
+bugs and gives compile-time guarantees that all levels exist. The "no network" property
+also makes Vitest unit tests of the loader trivial (no `fetch` mock needed). Use the modern
+Vite 5+ form `import.meta.glob('./levels/*.json', { eager: true, query: '?json', import: 'default' })`
+(verified: Vite 8.1.2 is current and supports this; the older `as: 'json'` form is
+deprecated in favor of `query: '?json'`). **Confidence: HIGH.**
+
+> Note: the assignment context listed the older `as: 'json'` syntax. That syntax was
+> deprecated in Vite 5; the `query: '?json'` / `import: 'default'` form is the current
+> equivalent and behaves identically. Either way the recommendation is the glob approach,
+> not the syntax. **Confidence: HIGH.**
+
+---
+
+### Direction 2 — State Management
+
+How game state (current level, grid, player/box positions, undo stack, move count, cleared
+levels) is held and observed by the renderer.
+
+| Criterion | A: Plain TS module/class + tiny `EventEmitter` (or `Emit`-style callback list) | B: Signals — `nanostores` or `@preact/signals` (v2.9.2) | C: Full framework (React/Solid) driving Canvas | Recommendation |
+|-----------|---------|---------|---------|---------|
+| Fits Canvas 2D render model (imperative draw loop) | **Perfect** — state mutates, render reads it each frame (HIGH) | Fine, but signals shine for DOM binding, not Canvas | Mismatch — framework diffing is for DOM, not Canvas; you still write a draw loop | A |
+| Bundle added | 0 (hand-rolled emitter ~20 lines) | ~1 KB (nanostores 1.4.0) / ~3.5 KB (preact/signals-core 1.14.3) | 40–100 KB+ | A |
+| Undo stack + move counter ergonomics | Trivial — arrays/numbers on a class, push/pop (HIGH) | Workable but signals over plain integers add ceremony | Overkill; state would live in framework store then be read into Canvas anyway | A |
+| Testability (Vitest) | Pure TS classes/functions → direct unit test, no DOM (HIGH) | Same, slightly more imports | Needs framework test setup (RTL etc.) | A |
+| Reactive UI bits (level picker, move counter text) | One small emitter + a few `addEventListener` on DOM nodes (~30 lines) | Signals bind to DOM text in 1 line each — marginal win | Best DX here, but the UI surface is ~5 nodes | A (signals would be acceptable if UI grows) |
+
+**Recommendation: A — plain TS module/class + minimal event emitter.** The render model is
+imperative Canvas; there is no virtual DOM to diff. The reactive surface is tiny (move
+counter, level picker, win banner, undo/reset buttons). A single `GameModel` class with a
+small `subscribe(listener)` method covers both the render loop and the few DOM labels
+without a dependency. **Confidence: HIGH.** (If the UI later grows to many bound elements,
+`nanostores` v1.4.0 is the cheapest upgrade path — note this in architecture.md, not now.)
+
+---
+
+### Direction 3 — Animation Library
+
+NFR-5: 100–150ms linear tween for player/box moves, parallel when pushing, interruptible
+by next input.
+
+| Criterion | A: Vanilla `requestAnimationFrame` linear tween (~30 lines) | B: `motion` (v12.42.2, formerly motion-one) | C: `anime.js` (v4.5.0) | D: CSS transitions on a DOM overlay | Recommendation |
+|-----------|---------|---------|---------|---------|---------|
+| Integrates with Canvas draw loop | **Yes** — tween advances a single `t∈[0,1]`, renderer reads interpolated tile coords (HIGH) | Designed for DOM/SVG `animate()`; can drive a number via `animate(0→1)` but you re-read it in rAF anyway | Same — JS lib, drives values, you still draw in rAF | **No** — CSS transitions target DOM styles, not Canvas pixel coords | A |
+| Linear easing only | `t = (now-start)/duration`, `lerp(a,b,t)` — one line (HIGH) | Supported but brings spring/keyframe machinery you won't use | Same | n/a | A |
+| Interruptibility (new move cancels in-flight) | Trivial: reset `start=now`, swap `from=current interpolated pos` (HIGH) | Cancellation API exists; more concepts to learn | `.pause()`/restart; heavier | CSS cancel mid-transition is awkward | A |
+| Bundle | 0 | ~16 KB (motion) | ~50 KB (anime v4) | 0 but wrong tool | A |
+| Risk of over-coupling to lib API | None | Low-medium | Medium | n/a | A |
+
+**Recommendation: A — vanilla rAF linear tween.** The animation spec is deliberately
+minimal (linear, 100–150ms, parallel, interruptible). A 30-line helper
+(`startTween(from, to, duration, onUpdate)` returning a cancel handle) satisfies every
+NFR-5 acceptance criterion, stays inside the existing render loop, and adds zero
+dependencies. Pulling in `motion` (16 KB) or `anime.js` (50 KB) to do a linear lerp is
+exactly the overengineering the project's simplicity-first principle forbids. **Confidence:
+HIGH.**
+
+---
+
+### Direction 4 — Touch Swipe Detection
+
+NFR-4: mobile swipe up/down/left/right for movement; on-screen undo/reset buttons.
+
+| Criterion | A: Native Pointer Events (`pointerdown`/`move`/`up` + threshold + directional lock) | B: Hammer.js (v2.0.8, unmaintained since 2016) | C: Custom touch events + heuristic thresholds (touchstart/touchend Δx/Δy) | Recommendation |
+|-----------|---------|---------|---------|---------|
+| Maintenance status | Native — always maintained (HIGH) | **Stale** — last release 2016, no Pointer Events, known touch-action bugs on iOS (HIGH) | Native — always maintained | A |
+| Bundle | 0 | ~20 KB | 0 | A |
+| Supports mouse + touch + pen uniformly | **Yes** — Pointer Events unify them; desktop drag-test works too (HIGH) | Touch/mouse only via separate recognizers | Touch only; mouse needs separate path | A |
+| Complexity for 4-direction swipe | ~25 lines: record start pos, on `pointerup` compare Δ, pick dominant axis, threshold ~24px, reset if below (HIGH) | Config object ` Hammer.Swipe({direction: ...})` — similar line count but a dep | ~20 lines, touch-only | A |
+| Passive listener / scroll handling | Set `touch-action: none` on canvas + `pointercancel` handling (HIGH) | Library manages but conflicts with page scroll on some browsers | Manual `e.preventDefault()` in touchmove (can block passive optimization) | A |
+
+**Recommendation: A — native Pointer Events.** Hammer.js is unmaintained (last release
+2016) and superseded by Pointer Events in all evergreen browsers. A single ~25-line
+`attachSwipe(canvas, onDirection)` helper using Pointer Events handles mouse, touch, and
+pen, costs nothing, and avoids the iOS `touch-action` pitfalls that Hammer still trips on.
+**Confidence: HIGH.** On-screen buttons use plain `click`/`pointerup` listeners.
+
+---
+
+### Direction 5 — localStorage Wrapper
+
+NFR-2: persist cleared level IDs + per-level best move counts; restore on load;
+clear-progress option.
+
+| Criterion | A: Vanilla `localStorage` (try/catch + `JSON.parse/stringify`) | B: `idb-keyval` (v6.2.6) | C: `localforage` (v1.10.0) | Recommendation |
+|-----------|---------|---------|---------|---------|
+| Storage needed | < 1 KB (≤10 level IDs + ≤10 best counts) → fits `localStorage` 5 MB easily (HIGH) | Same data, but IndexedDB backing | Same, IndexedDB + driver fallback | A |
+| Synchronous read on page load | **Yes** — `localStorage.getItem` is sync; restore before first paint (HIGH) | **No** — async `get()`, must await on boot | **No** — async | A |
+| Bundle | 0 | ~1 KB | ~30 KB | A |
+| Safari private-mode quirks | `localStorage` throws → one try/catch wrapper handles it (HIGH) | IndexedDB works in private mode but more moving parts | Heavier | A |
+| Need for structured/binary data | None — two flat objects | None | None | A |
+
+**Recommendation: A — vanilla `localStorage`.** The persisted shape is two tiny flat
+objects (cleared IDs array, best-counts map) totaling well under 1 KB. IndexedDB wrappers
+(`idb-keyval`, `localforage`) exist to solve *async/structured/large* storage problems this
+project does not have, and their async API would force a boot-time await for state that
+could otherwise restore synchronously. A single `storage.ts` module with `loadProgress()`
+and `saveProgress()` wrapping `try/catch` around `JSON.parse`/`stringify` is the correct
+size. **Confidence: HIGH.**
+
+---
+
+### Direction 6 — Game Loop Architecture
+
+How input, simulation, and rendering are scheduled.
+
+| Criterion | A: rAF render loop + input-driven immediate simulation (no fixed timestep) | B: Fixed-timestep simulation + interpolation render (classic game loop) | C: Event-driven: redraw only on state change (no continuous loop) | Recommendation |
+|-----------|---------|---------|---------|---------|
+| Matches the "move = one tile + 100–150ms tween" model | **Yes** — input mutates state, rAF advances tween and redraws (HIGH) | Built for continuous physics (60 Hz sim); Sokoban has no continuous physics | Works but tween still needs a loop; end up with a hybrid | A |
+| Frame-rate independence for the tween | Use `performance.now()` deltas → tween duration is real-ms regardless of fps (HIGH) | Yes, but heavier | n/a | A |
+| Complexity | ~40 lines: `requestAnimationFrame(loop)`, compute `t`, draw, cancel when tween done | ~120 lines (accumulator, step cap, alpha interpolation) | Mixed | A |
+| Battery on mobile | Loop can stop when no tween active and restart on input (HIGH) | Always running | Best, but breaks tween continuity if naively implemented | A (with idle-stop) |
+
+**Recommendation: A — single rAF loop, input mutates state immediately, loop advances the
+active tween (if any) and redraws; loop idles (no-op) when no animation is running to save
+mobile battery, restarting on next input.** Fixed-timestep is the right tool for
+continuous physics (platformers, sims), not for a discrete puzzle with short linear
+tweens. **Confidence: HIGH.** The renderer reads model state each frame, so no separate
+"render queue" is needed.
+
+---
+
+### Direction 7 — Testing Specifics
+
+Vitest (unit) + Playwright (E2E) are locked. Open: DOM emulation for unit tests, and
+Playwright config for a static build + mobile viewport.
+
+#### 7a — Vitest DOM environment
+
+| Criterion | A: `happy-dom` (v20.10.6) | B: `jsdom` (v29.1.1) | C: No DOM env (pure logic only) | Recommendation |
+|-----------|---------|---------|---------|---------|
+| Speed | **Fast** — significantly faster than jsdom, lower memory (MEDIUM-HIGH; widely reported) | Slower; heavier | Fastest | A |
+| Canvas 2D support | Neither implements real Canvas 2D; both stub `getContext` → must mock `CanvasRenderingContext2D` in tests anyway (HIGH) | Same | n/a | Tie (both need canvas mock) |
+| Needed for unit tests | Move/push/win/undo/persistence/level-loading logic is pure TS → **no DOM needed**; only the swipe/emitter/DOM-label tests want a DOM (HIGH) | Same | Pure logic skips DOM entirely | A only for the few DOM-touching tests; `environmentMatchGlobs` can scope it |
+| Maintenance / Vitest compat | happy-dom is a Vitest-recommended default; vitest 4.1.9 lists it as a peer (HIGH) | jsdom also listed as peer (HIGH) | n/a | A |
+| Bundle | ~3 MB dev dep | ~25 MB dev dep (jsdom + deps) | 0 | A |
+
+**Recommendation: A — `happy-dom`** as the default Vitest environment, with pure-logic
+tests still runnable without DOM. Canvas operations are mocked via a small
+`vi.stubGlobal('HTMLCanvasElement', …)` / `ctx` spy — required under either happy-dom or
+jsdom since neither renders real Canvas 2D. Scope happy-dom via `environmentMatchGlobs` to
+test files that actually touch `document`, keeping pure-logic tests environment-free.
+**Confidence: HIGH** on the choice; **MEDIUM** on the exact mock shape (verify against the
+real `ctx` calls during implementation).
+
+#### 7b — Playwright config for static build + mobile viewport
+
+| Criterion | A: `webServer` serving `vite preview` on `dist/` + `projects` for desktop & mobile | B: `webServer` serving `vite dev` | C: `npx http-server dist/` ad-hoc | Recommendation |
+|-----------|---------|---------|---------|---------|
+| Tests the actual deploy artifact | **Yes** — `vite build` → `vite preview` serves the real static bundle (HIGH) | No — dev server differs from prod (no bundling/base handling) | Yes but extra dep + manual lifecycle | A |
+| Mobile viewport | `projects: [{ name:'mobile', use:{...devices['Pixel 7'], isMobile:true, hasTouch:true} }, { name:'desktop', use:{ viewport:{width:1280,height:720} } }]` (HIGH) | Same | Same | A |
+| `base` for GitHub Pages repo subdir | Verified in `vite preview` with `base` set; tests must navigate to `BASE_URL` (HIGH) | Dev server ignores prod base | Manual | A |
+| Parallelism / CI cost | Two projects × N tests; fine for 10 levels | Same | Same | A |
+
+**Recommendation: A — Playwright `webServer` running `vite preview` against the built
+`dist/`, with two `projects` (desktop viewport + a mobile touch device preset).** This
+exercises the exact static bundle GitHub Pages will serve, including the `base` path
+configuration, and the mobile project gives real touch/swipe coverage for NFR-4. CI
+command: `npm run build && npx playwright test` (or a `test:e2e` script). **Confidence:
+HIGH.**
+
+---
+
+## Final Selection
+
+| Component | Choice | Version | Purpose | Confidence |
+|-----------|--------|---------|---------|------------|
